MySQL primary key is a single or combination of the field, which is used to identify each record in a table uniquely. If the column contains primary key constraints, then it cannot be null

# Primary key
i. It is a single or combination of the field, which is used to identify each record in a table uniquely

ii. It does not allow to store a NULL value into the primary key column.

iii. A table can have only one primary key.

iv. It create a clustered index.


# unique key

i. It also determines each row of the table uniquely in the absence of a primary key

ii. It can accept only one NULL value into the unique key column
iii. A table can have more than one unique key.

iv. It creates a non-clustered index